  "notes": [
    {
      "title": "Arabic Numbers 1-10",
      "titleArabic": "الْأَعْدَاد",
      "content": [
        "Arabic numbers 1-10 have a unique rule: numbers 3-10 show reverse gender agreement with the counted noun. If the noun is masculine, the number takes the feminine form (with ة), and vice versa.",
        "Numbers 1 and 2 agree with the noun normally. The counted noun after numbers 3-10 is plural and in the genitive case."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "Numbers 3-10 have 'reverse' gender agreement with the noun",
        "With masculine nouns: ثَلَاثَةُ كُتُبٍ (three books - number has ة)",
        "With feminine nouns: ثَلَاثُ سَيَّارَاتٍ (three cars - number without ة)",
        "The counted noun is plural genitive after numbers 3-10"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "وَاحِدٌ، اِثْنَانِ، ثَلَاثَةٌ", "english": "one, two, three" },
        { "arabic": "أَرْبَعَةٌ، خَمْسَةٌ، سِتَّةٌ", "english": "four, five, six" },
        { "arabic": "سَبْعَةٌ، ثَمَانِيَةٌ، تِسْعَةٌ، عَشَرَةٌ", "english": "seven, eight, nine, ten" },
        { "arabic": "ثَلَاثَةُ كُتُبٍ", "english": "three books" }
      ]
    }
  ],
